KEYWORDS
GLP-1; neuroprotection;
stroke; parkinson; alzheimer
Introduction
First identified in the early 1980s, GLP-1 is an incretin hor-
mone, derived from pre-proglucagon and released mostly from
the L-cells located at the distal ileum and colon (1). Primary
peripheric functions of GLP-1 are inducing insulin secretion
from pancreatic beta cells, gut emptying and inhibiting gluca-
gon secretion which results in lower blood glucose levels. GLP-
1 also enhances cell proliferation, differentiation, and protec-
tion via anti-apoptotic properties on pancreatic beta cells (2,3).
Continuous native GLP-1 administration enhances insulin
levels and results in lower blood glucose and hemoglobin
A1C levels in patients with type 2 diabetes mellitus (T2DM)
(4). Currently, GLP-1 agonists exenatide and liraglutide, that
have a longer half-life compared to GLP-1, are approved drugs
used for the treatment of T2DM and research on other effective
GLP-1 analogs continues. Endogenous GLP-1 is degraded by
the enzyme dipeptidyl peptidase IV (DPP-IV). This makes
DPP-IV another important target for T2DM therapies as inhi-
bition of DPP-IV by agents as sitagliptin, resulting in an
increase in circulating GLP-1 levels (1).
Apart from its peripheral actions, GLP-1 released into the
bloodstream readily crosses the blood-brain barrier and accesses
central and peripheral nervous system for extra-pancreatic
actions. The exact mechanism of peripheral GLP-1’s entry to
the CNS is not well understood as native GLP-1 is rapidly
inactivated. One mechanism on the interaction between periph-
eral GLP-1 and the brain (5), suggests that circulating GLP-1
binds to GLP-1 receptors (GLP-1R) on vagal afferents and access
the brain through the GLP-1R on the nucleus of the solitary tract
(NTS) in the hindbrain and arcuate nucleus of the hypothalamus
(ARC). GLP-1 neurons in the brain project to vagal efferents
which in turn send descending output to the pancreas and
increase insulin secretion (6).
In the central nervous system (CNS), GLP-1 can also be
produced by neurons, which are mostly located in the nucleus
of solitary tract (NST) of the hindbrain, that project to mid-
brain and forebrain areas such as the ventral tegmental area
(VTA), nucleus accumbens (NAc) and hypothalamus (7). In
addition, they can be secreted by microglial cells when stimu-
lated by cAMP and by transforming proglucagon. Prolonged
inflammatory processes lead to a decrease in this transforma-
tion and a decrease in microglia derived GLP-1 levels (8).
GLP-1R are widely expressed in the periphery and regions
of the CNS including the hippocampus, neocortex, hypotha-
lamus, and cerebellum (7). All GLP-1Rs are G-protein
coupled receptors (GPCRs), which act mainly via activation
of adenylyl cyclase and subsequent increase in cAMP and
intracellular calcium resulting in glucose-dependent insulin
exocytosis
(9).
