GLP-1Rs
are
mostly
expressed on dendrites and synapses in a subpopulation of
output neurons such as pyramidal, dentate granule, and
Purkinje cells. GLP-1R might possibly be expressed in glial
cells as well (11); in addition, they may induce GLP-1 expres-
sion during inflammatory responses (12). Previous research
also implicates growth factor-like properties of GLP-1 (13).
GLP-1 enhances neuronal growth and reduces apoptosis
through cAMP-dependent signaling cascades and GLP-1R
upregulation. GLP-1R overexpression promotes learning of
spatial tasks and deletion of GLP-1R impairs memory forma-
tion and synaptic plasticity (14). Furthermore, GLP-1 admin-
istration results in glutamate release and enhanced firing in
the hippocampus. These results show that GLP-1 acts as
a neuromodulator in neurotransmitter release, synaptic plas-
ticity and have important neuroprotective properties (7).
Emerging evidence also suggests that GLP-1 may be useful
for neuroprotection in animal models of Alzheimer’s Disease
(AD), Parkinson’s disease (PD) (15). However, the mechan-
isms of GLP-1 actions on neuroprotection, its molecular and
cellular effectors, and the resulting benefits are still not fully
understood. Also, current reviews focusing on the neuropro-
tective effects of GLP-1 on neuroprotection focus on one
neurodegenerative disorder. Therefore, in this systematic
review, we aimed to systematically analyze the neuroprotec-
tive role of GLP-1 and its currently identified mechanisms
that provide neuroprotection, to establish a fuller framework
on the effects of GLP-1 based on existing literature. Because of
the heterogeneity in the methods and aims of the studies, we
