Methods
Search strategy
This study was conducted in accordance with the PRISMA
(16) and MOOSE (17) guidelines, as suggested for conducting
systematic reviews. Web of Science and Pubmed have been
searched to reach all relevant articles that use ‘glucagon-like
peptide-1’, ‘GLP-1’, ‘glucagon-like peptide-1 receptor’, ‘GLP-
1R’ in their title, abstract or as a keyword. Online search was
completed on September 5, 2018. Nineteen thousand seven
hundred and twenty-one articles on Web of Science and
14203 on Pubmed were found. All articles have been down-
loaded as a list of abstracts and 8150 duplicates among the
two databases have been removed, by CYE, using endnote.
CYE, DE, UK, and CD inspected the list for identifying
possible articles that included relevant information about
GLP-1 and brain. Abstracts not about psychiatry, neurology
or neuroscience have been excluded. In the first identification
step, original articles, in addition to reviews were downloaded
in full text, to catch references that may have not been
covered by our search strategy. In the screening step, CYE,
DE, UK, and CD read all abstracts to identify articles that
possibly included data about GLP-1 and neuroprotection and
HYE checked the final lists for agreement of two authors. In
case abstracts were inconclusive, the full article was accessed
to study their relevance. Only articles published in English
could be involved. Poster and conference proceedings were
excluded as quality criteria. Only nine articles with possibly
relevant information could not be accessed full text and there-
fore, could not be included.
Study selection
For study selection, identified original articles have been
screened for topic and methods. Articles mainly on the phar-
macology of GLP-1 that are not related with the nervous
system, GLP-1’s effect on metabolic symptoms of diabetes,
satiety, feeding behavior, and reward systems have been
excluded. Special emphasis was put on articles that studied
Parkinson’s disease, Alzheimer’s disease, stroke, traumatic
brain injury, cognitive functions, and nervous system’s cellu-
lar components. Studies using neuroinflammation models as
LPS injection, multiple sclerosis, and experimental autoim-
mune encephalomyelitis were not included. Studies conducted
solely on C. elegans have been excluded. Studies using DPP-4
inhibitors have also been included as they act by increasing
GLP-1 levels.
Data extraction
Articles were grouped for preclinical and clinical studies.
Preclinical studies were further grouped for models of
Parkinson’s disease, Alzheimer’s disease, stroke, traumatic
brain injury, epilepsy, metabolic neurodegeneration that
included streptozotocin models for inducing diabetes and
high-fat diet, neurogenesis and neuroplasticity, and, lastly,
studies on cell cultures. Even though seizure generation is
not always related to neurodegeneration, we included seizure
models to this study, since it may point to glutamatergic
neurodegeneration pathways.
For preclinical studies, the name of the first author,
publication year, mouse/rat line, the definition of the neuro-
degenerative model, GLP-1 agonist type, dose, administration
method and duration, experimental groups in the study,
molecular assessments, behavioral assessments, electrophysio-
logical assessments, and main results have been extracted. For
human clinical studies, the sample size of the study, charac-
teristics of the research groups, GLP-1 agonist type, dose,
administration method and duration, main outcome mea-
sures, and main results have been extracted.
All extracted data have been controlled by at least two
authors. Studies that worked on cognitive behaviors, but did
not provide information about molecular and cellular aspects
of neuroprotection were excluded.
Studies on preclinical models of Parkinson’s disease have
been grouped under the lesion model as 6-OHDA model,
MPTP model, and rotenone model. Studies on preclinical
models of Alzheimer’s disease have been grouped under amy-
loid beta experimental models, transgenic models, and strep-
tozotocin
model,
which
linked
diabetes
with
the
neuropathology of Alzheimer’s disease through Ab protein
or tau protein. Clinical studies on human subjects have been
grouped and presented separately.
We did not use a quality scoring method based on the
studies’ methodology, since most of the studies were con-
ducted on animal models. But, as a quality assessment, we
expected articles to fully explain the lesion model and usage of
GLP mimetics, in addition to the timing and design of mole-
cular and behavioral outcome measures. Each study should
have appropriate control groups. Studies from the same
research groups were checked for overlapping data of animals
or clinical populations.
Since studies were conducted on heterogeneous groups of
animals and on clinical samples with various outcome focuses,
we could not conduct a meta-analysis statistics of the pooled
data. Rather, we preferred to present the extracted data as
grouped tables. Publication bias also could not be statistically
analyzed due to the heterogeneity of the outcome variables in
the studies
Demonstration of the findings
Main outcomes that this systematic review focused on were
the behavioral effects of GLP mimetics that may imply neu-
roprotection when compared to lesion/ neurotoxicity models
and molecular effects of GLP mimetics that may explain the
mechanism of action for GLP-1 in neuroprotection.
Since how the neurodegenerative model was inducted and
dose and application method of GLP-1 are important vari-
ables that affect the outcome, we preferred to present them in
the results tables, with behavioral and molecular assessment
methods that may interest future researchers. Since we espe-
cially wanted to focus on the neuroprotective effects, major
