findings section summarized the effect of GLP-MA compared
to the lesion or neurotoxic agent exposed groups, mainly.
Studies solely studying long-term potentiation (LTP) as
a variable affected by GLP-1, have been grouped under neu-
roplasticity and neurogenesis title. Studies on the retina and
amyotrophic lateral sclerosis models were included under
neuropathy title, with studies that assessed streptozotocin-
induced damage on motor neuron fibers. Studies conducted
on cell cultures have been grouped together, regardless of the
molecular and cellular mechanism studied. Studies that
included data about more than one neuroprotection system
as Bertilson et al. (18), where both GLP-1 agonists effect on
neurogenesis and protection against 6-OHDA induced lesions
were reported, are presented in both tables.
Results
Description of the included studies and the study
characteristics
After identification, screening and data extraction, 289 studies
were included for the systematic review (Figure 1). Current
studies focusing on neuroprotective effects of GLP-1 agonists
worked on models of Parkinson’s disease (18–41), Alzheimer’s
disease (13,42–94), metabolic syndrome (95–124) ischemia
(35,125–147), traumatic brain injury (148–165), neuropathies
(166–191), neurogenesis (11,14,192–212), epilepsy (213–218),
and cell cultures of neurons (13,35,56,91,219–252), astrocytes
(253) and monocyte/microglia (254). Transgenic models were
used for modeling Alzheimer’s disease (64–83), Huntington
disease (255,256), multiple system atrophy (257), amyotrophic
lateral sclerosis (183,184), diabetes (13,83,166,185,198) and
obesity (198,199) . Relatively lower number of studies were
found to be conducted on human subjects (258–265). These
clinical trials included Alzheimer’s disease (258–), Parkinson’s
disease (259–), metabolic syndromes (261,263), schizophrenia
(262), elderly patients (), and patients with diabetes with
a retinopathy history (265).
GLP-1 agonists used in studies were liraglutide, lixisena-
tide, exenatide, exendin-4 (EX-4) or natural GLP-1 hormone.
DPP-4 inhibitors were linagliptin, sitagliptin, saxagliptin and
vildagliptin. Geniposide was also used as a GLP-1 mimetic.
DA-JC1 (GLP-1/GIP) and other dual agonists were also stu-
died. All of these have been grouped under the name of GLP-
1 modifying agents (GLP-MA) in this review.
Findings from preclinical studies on Parkinson’s disease
models
Preclinical studies that studied the effects of GLP-1 mimetics
on PD’s models are listed and summarized in Table 1. Main
behavioral assessment for quantifying the motor effects of
Parkinson’s disease models in preclinical studies was apomor-
phine or amphetamine-induced rotation test (18,19); however,
other motor assessments as an open field test and swim test
were also used. Since studies used different mouse/rat strains
and lesion models, it was hard to combine findings and
compare for replications. Liraglutide (19) and saxagliptin
(25) tested on moderate to severe degree of dopaminergic
neuron loss were not effective to reverse the effects of
6-OHDA on dopaminergic neurons and associated behaviors.
However, exendin-4 tested on different strains of rats in
different studies, was effective to avoid 6-OHDA induced
dopaminergic neuron loss and to decrease rotating behavior
induced by either apomorphine or amphetamine (18,22,23)
(Table 1). In addition, this effect was observed in neuroin-
flammation models and exendin-4 was successful for increas-
ing the number of neural stem cells in the subventricular
zone, in Parkinson’s disease models (18,20,23). However, in
other neurodegenerative models of Parkinson’s disease in
mice, EX-4 was either non-effective or partially effective to
reserve motor impairments and TH positive neuron loss
induced by MPTP and the effect of DPP-4 inhibitors was
found to be superior to its effects (26). In addition, generally,
GLP-MA were not as effective in reversing the impairments
induced by MPTP models as 6-OHDA models and most of
their use had partial improvement (Table 1). Suggested
mechanisms for this partial improvement were decreasing
inflammatory
factors
as
TGF-b,
TNF-a
and
IL-10
(21,27,33,34,38–40), inhibition of microglial activation (41),
increased GDNF expression (21,30,31,39), increased BDNF
expression (38), altering Akt phosphorylation (21,29), redu-
cing Bax and increasing Bcl-2 levels (26,29,32,33,36,38,39),
reducing cytochrome c and caspase-3 levels (37,38), increas-
ing synapse numbers (28). Preclinical evidence also supports
that newly developed GLP-1 mimetics may show better ben-
efits compared to GLP-1 agonists alone.
Findings from studies on preclinical Alzheimer’s disease
models
Preclinical studies on Alzheimer’s models use either strepto-
zotocin, amyloid beta, and transgenic animal models (13,42–
85) . In all models, GLP-MA are shown to have a dose
dependent protective effect against Alzheimer disease neuro-
pathology and behavioral symptoms except for exenatide on
3xTg-AD mice model (67) and liraglutide on two transgenic
models (73) (Table 2). These studies also add on to literature
on Parkinson’s disease by assessing the dynamic synaptic
modeling process through long-term potentiation (LTP).
Streptozocin model, in conjunction with high fat diet, induced
Alzheimer like pathology as increased phosphorylated tau
proteins, chronic inflammation, and structural changes in
hippocampus and decreased performance on cognitive tasks
(42–49). However, GLP-MA could partially reverse cognitive
dysfunction related with the model and preserve hippocampal
morphology, decrease inflammation and apoptosis markers as
well as phospho-tau protein levels (Table 2a). Studies on
amyloid beta models (13,50–63), showed that the effect of
GLP-MA on tau phosphorylation is also observed in non-
diabetic models. GLP-MA not only improves hippocampal
dependent learning, but it may also improve circadian
rhythms (51). In transgenic animal models (64–85), even
though GLP-MA may not change total tau levels, they
decrease phospho-tau levels and improve cognitive function-
ing even in triple transgenic animals (Table 2c). This effect
was prominent on studies using spatial learning tasks; how-
ever, the effect of recognition memory was not well studied,
