D. ERBIL ET AL.
and it was even found to be not affected by liraglutide in one
study (73) (Table 2c). Age of the animals may have led to this
conflicting finding. Among the investigated GLP-MA, Ex-4
was less effective when results of individual studies are com-
pared, even though not tested as a head-to-head comparison
(Table 2). Investigated underlying mechanisms for this GLP-
1's effect on Alzheimer’s disease neuropathology were similar
as GSK-3 (42,44,45,47,50,57,63,64,68,70,72,87,88,92) and Akt
(42,47,50,63,68,72) phosphorylation, increased cAMP (58),
p-CREB levels (52,64,), decrease of activated microglia cells
(43,71,79), decreasing inflammatory factors as TGF-b, TNF-a
and IL-10 (46,,49,74,76), reducing Bax and increasing bcl-2
levels (43,54), reducing cytochrome c and caspase-3 levels
(54), reducing oxidative stress (71), decreased NFkb signaling
(74), increased neurogenesis (76,77,82), increased BDNF (89),
signaling through cAMP, glutamatergic receptor distribution
and LTP (74) (Table 2b). Val(8)GLP-1 was ineffective for
decreasing age related microglial activation in APP/PS1–21
mice model (69).
Findings from models of metabolic syndrome
Streptozocin model was not only used to investigate tau
pathology and associated hippocampal damage, but also to
study the effects of metabolic changes (95–108). In rats
exposed to streptozotocin to disrupt glucose metabolism,
GLP-MA improved both spatial memory and working mem-
ory, increase neurotrophic factors as BDNF (95,98,106),
increae dphosphorylation of Akt and GSK-3b (100,104,107),
reduce the levels of COX1, COX2, and NF-kB (96,106),
reduced activation of microglia cells (96), protected blood
brain barrier integrity by increasing occludin and aquaporin-
4 levels (99), decreased proinflammatory factors as TNF-a
(98,103), reduced oxidative stress (106), decreased apoptosis
(108) and enhanced autophagy through the activation of
AMPK/mTOR pathway (108) (Table 3). In animals fed with
high fat diet, GLP-MA not only helped to reduce body weight
and balance the glucose tolerance, but also to improve recog-
nition memory, LTP formation and synaptic strength (109–
124), except for GLP-1 (9–36), GIP (3–42) and exendin (9–39)
reported in one article (110) (Table 3b). In addition to pre-
vious neuroprotective mechanisms explored, these studies also
add a mechanism for protecting against Alzheimer disease
development, by protecting synapse numbers (112–114),
healthy cell numbers (118,) and increased insulin sensitivity
(116,121,122).
Findings from studies on preclinical studies on ischemia
and trauma
Ischemia is a common clinical problem which needs further
treatments. Middle cerebral artery occlusion model (MCAO)
is a model of ischemia used both in rats and mice. Given
either before, immediately after or days after stroke induction
by MCAO, GLP-MA decrease the infarction volume, which
correlates with better behavioral test scores (125–147) (Table
4). In MCAO models, GLP-MA are shown to increase neuro-
vascular intensity and increase vascular proliferation by
increasing Bcl-2 levels (125,131,132) and decreasing caspase-
