47
3 levels (128,146), decreasing inflammatory factors (), altering
cAMP-PKA-CREB
signaling
(125,126,128,146),
inhibiting
oxidative stress (126,131,132), increasing BDNF () and
VEGF (139), increasing healthy and proliferating cell numbers
(130,138) and microvessel density () (Table 4a). GLP-MA also
affects traumatic brain injury (TBI) related changes in the
brain (148–165). Keeping the integrity of blood-brain barrier
and avoiding apoptosis are among the significant mechanisms
for this finding, in addition to reducing cerebral edema size
(153) (Table 4b). On the other hand, increased inflammatory
factors were not found to be a significant modulating effect of
sitagliptin on TBI ().
Findings from studies on preclinical epilepsy models
GLP-MA significantly affected seizure severity and decreased
seizure
model
induced
inflammation
and
apoptosis
(213–218). Changes in levels of neurotransmitters of GABA,
glutamate, and serotonin could be mediating this effect
(Table 5).
Findings from studies on neurogenesis and
neuroplasticity
Administration of GLP-MA increased neurogenesis and neu-
roplasticity (14,192–212) as measured by Brd-U positive cells
and LTP, whereas antagonism of GLP-1R reduced cell prolif-
eration in the rat brain and GLP-1 levels are predictive of
adult neurogenesis even in macaques. Localization of GLP-1R
on the synaptic buttons of hippocampus and cortex and its
effect on increased cAMP through second messenger coupling
might be mediating neurogenesis. When neurotrophic factors
were investigated, increased synthesis of VEGF was seen
(197), but levels of BDNF and tyrosine kinase receptor type-
2, which is also a receptor for BDNF, were found contra-
dictory (195,199) (Table 6). As a marker for synaptic plasticity
and synaptic receptor trafficking, studies link these findings
also with enhanced LTP, which is the basic mechanism for
learning and memory and indirect measures of GABA and
glutamate signaling (Table 6).
Findings from studies on peripheral neurological effects
on animal models
GLP-1 receptors are expressed on peripheral nerves, as well
(170). Studies investigating the role of GLP-MA on peripheral
nervous system mainly used streptozotocin models similar to
metabolic models and measured motor neuron activity, motor
neuron integrity and motor neuron conduction, in addition to
behavioral assessments as pain sensitivity and locomotor
activity (166–191). GLP-MA preserve the pain sensitivity
and conductive capacity of motor neurons, myelin fiber den-
sity and schwann cell viability (166–191) (Table 7a).
GLP-1R is also expressed in retina and GLP-1 agonists
reverse diabetes-induced increase in glutamate and diabetes-
related neuron loss in the retina; however, functional and
morphological improvements were not observed in the long
term (Table 7b).
