ALS was also modeled in animals with SOD or transgenic
familial ALS mice. In these models, GLP-MA were successful
for increasing cell viability and decreasing delaying symptom
onsets and improving motor neuron functions (Table 7c).
Findings from cell cultures
When studied on neurodegeneration or neurotoxicity models,
GLP-MA dose dependently protected neurons from oxidative
stress, as studied on ventromedial cortex, hippocampus and neu-
roblastoma cells (13,35,56,84,94,,,,219–254). GLP-MA increased
neuronal survival as well as nourish neurite outgrowth (223,,237)
possibly by modulating glutamate induced calcium currents. This
GLP-1R-dependent action is also found to be mediated via the
protein kinase A (PKA), phosphoinositide 3-kinase (PI3K) and
Akt/Erk/mTOR signaling pathways, with the mitogen-activated
protein
kinase
(MAPK)
pathway
playing
a
minor
role
(222,,230,232,236,238,245,254). GLP-MA also helped restore
intracellular calcium levels and protect against apoptosis by
decreasing Bax1 levels and increasing Bcl-2 (219,220,248). One
other studied mechanism is also increasing BDNF levels in the
microglia (254)(Table 8).
Findings from clinical studies and human subjects
One of the earliest studies that measured GLP-1 levels in
a small sample of patients with Alzheimer’s disease could
not find a significant difference between patients and controls
in GLP-1 levels (258). Studies that followed in later years,
focused on the effects of exatinide or liraglutide for studying
neuroprotective actions of GLP-MA, regardless of the baseline
GLP-1 levels (258–265). GLP-MA are generally well tolerated
by human subjects. Use of these agents for longer than 3–6
months was found to improve cognitive symptoms in patients
with Alzheimer disease and motor symptoms in patients with
Parkinson’s disease, while control groups experienced more
deterioration in their symptoms (Table 9). However, there
was no significant effect of liraglutide on Alzheimer’s disease
neuropathology as measured by the deposition of beta-
amyloid in the brain (). These beneficial effects of GLP-MA
seem to be dose and time-dependent and with a moderate
impact (Table 9).
Other studies not presented in the tables
The effect of GLP-MA has also been studied in models of
spinal cord injury, subarachnoid hemorrhage, intracerebral
hemorrhage, carotid artery occlusion, radiation injury, multi-
system atrophy and Huntington’s disease (255–257,266–273).
These studies have been presented in the supplementary table
for interested readers.
Discussion
To our knowledge, this study is the most up to date and com-
prehensive review of current evidence about GLP-1’s effect on
neuroprotection, considering its scope on not only Alzheimer’s
and Parkinson’s diseases, but other disorders that may also cause
neurodegenerative
outcomes.
By
searching
two
different
databases and carefully checking the references of reviews for
reference catching, we believe that we could cover all recent
information on this topic. Our current review demonstrates
the benefits of GLP-1R stimulation on multiple disorders like
Alzheimer’s, Parkinson’s, vascular occlusion, trauma, metabolic
degeneration, seizure, and even Huntington’s disease.
GLP-1 is an important molecule to protect against the
neurobiological changes observed in Alzheimer’s disease.
Even in early stages of AD, deficiencies in glucose utilization
and energy metabolism are commonly seen and the actions of
GLP-1 in the brain look similar to its role in protection,
proliferation, and differentiation of pancreatic beta cells in
the periphery. GLP-MA may not change body weight, blood
glucose, or insulin levels of animals; however, they decrease
insulin resistance in the brain and have a profound neuro-
protective effect (Table 1–8). Brain insulin resistance in AD
has been associated with cognitive decline, and biochemical
impairments and epidemiological studies show that indivi-
duals with T2DM have increased the risk of developing neu-
rodegenerative disorders at later stages (274). In T2DM
animal models, GLP-1 agonist administration prevents tau
hyperphosphorylation, which is an important neurodegenera-
tive feature of AD (275). Studies using streptozotocin models
and Alzheimer’s disease models show a connection between
how diabetes and metabolic syndrome may cause Alzheimer’s
disease and increased tau pathology (42–48). Studies with
GLP-1 shows that reducing brain insulin resistance may also
protect against tau phosphorylation (42).
In terms of synaptic plasticity, rodent studies show that
GLP-1R stimulation and GLP-1R agonist administration pro-
motes LTP and enhances hippocampus-dependent associative
and spatial learning (208). Co-treatment with GLP-1R antago-
nist reverses these effects suggesting the improvements are
mediated by GLP-1 signaling. On the other hand, GLP-1R
knockouts display LTP impairments and have deficits in
memory formation in various tasks including object recogni-
tion, Morris Water Maze and contextual fear learning perfor-
mance (14). So, GLP-1 is also important for synaptic strength,
new synapse formation, and neurogenesis.
The mechanism of action for GLP-1 in various neurode-
generative or neurodestructive disorders summarized in this
review looks similar and shared regardless of the pathology.
Molecular assessments mainly point out that the positive
effects of GLP-1 agonists and DPP-4 inhibitors might be
through reducing inflammation, increasing anti-apoptotic
proteins as Bcl-2 and increasing the number of neural stem
cells in the subventricular zone, which may compensate for
the neuron loss (29). Another mechanism of action for GLP-1
in the brain could be through strengthening the blood-brain
barrier. Indirect evidence from sodium butyrate use in MPTP
mice model points out that it both increases GLP-1 levels and
activates GLP-1 receptors in the brain; in addition, it strength-
ens the blood-brain barrier (276). Fukuda (277) also sup-
ported this finding with their experiments in cell cultures.
Lastly, GLP-1 changes phosphorylation levels of many critical
molecules as GSK-3b, Akt, Erk and mTOR (Table 1–8), which
might have a downstream modulator effect on other key
modules important for the viability of the cells. On the
other hand, many of the studies found that GLP-MA change
