D. ERBIL ET AL.
LTP, Bcl-2, and Bax1 levels in addition to modifying excito-
toxicity. Glutamate system and NMDA receptors could also
be a possible target of GLP-MA that mediate the neuropro-
tection, apoptosis and calcium signaling. Studies on seizure
models also support the fact that GLP-1R modifies cortical
excitability (Table 5). Studies with LTP assessed the contribu-
tion of AMPA receptor localization to some degree (Table 6);
however, further studies are needed to study GLP-1 -
glutamate receptor trafficking interactions. In addition, the
role of GLP-1 receptors and variable expression of these
receptors in different brains are not well studied. For
a better understanding and summary of the recent findings
from the current literature, we documented this knowledge in
Figure 2.
Literature suggests that GLP-1 agonists or DPP-4 inhibi-
tors both affect the outcome and have significant effects on
neuroprotection, but not all GLP-MA have the same neuro-
protective effect and also that the effect of GLP-MA on
reversing neurodegenerative or neurodestructive processes
might be time and dose-dependent. Generally, higher doses
of GLP-MA showed better effects in preclinical models. GLP-
1/GIP dual agonists are found to be more effective than GLP-
1 agonists alone (30,31). With their protease-resistant GLP-1
mimetic effects and longer duration of action, they may be
better candidates for neuroprotection. We believe that higher
number of studies that compare GLP-MA with each other and
assess the molecular systems attached with each GLP-MA
may pave the way for better CNS drugs and neuroprotection
mechanisms.
When studies are discussed from the human clinical trials
perspective on neurodegenerative disorders, current clinical stu-
dies have the disadvantage of recruiting patients that have
already been diagnosed with a degenerative disorder (Table 9).
However, animal studies are mostly conducted with concomi-
tant degeneration forming and GLP-MA administration, which
prevents neurodegenerative processes. On the other hand, stu-
dies from animal models of TBI and stroke point out that GLP-
MA could be protective against neuronal loss both if used before
(125,132,134,137,147,156,157,160,163) or after stroke or injury
(Table 4). However, studies on human subject focus mainly on
their cardiovascular effects and report stroke as another cardio-
vascular outcome that is modified by GLP-MA (278). As
Darsalia et al. suggest (278), this approach limits the translation
of animal studies to humans, as the only protective effect of GLP-
MA is not through avoiding vascular and peripheric effects of
diabetes, but they also have a central neuroprotective effect,
which can lead to their use for decreasing infarct sizes and
neuronal damage even after traumatic injury or vascular events.
Clinical studies also have a very small sample size and have
limited capacity for generalizability. In addition, they do not
give the opportunity to evaluate the mediating role of personal
factors, as body mass index, chronic stress and intellectual level
Figure 2. The mechanisms and effects of GLP-1 modulating agents on neuroprotection. Glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1) modulating agents, such as GLP-1 agonists
and DPP-4 inhibitors, act on the brain through similar and shared mechanisms to exert neuroprotection regardless of pathology in various neurodegenerative or
neurodestructive disorders. Common mechanisms are listed on the right side, and specific molecular pathways are listed on the left. GLP-1 decreases apoptosis by
increasing anti-apoptotic proteins as bcl-2 and decreasing pro-apoptotic proteins as cytochrome c, caspase 3, and bax. GLP-1 increases cell viability and restore
neurite outgrowth by increasing cAMP, PKA and CREB levels and changing phosphorylation levels of critical molecules as GSK-3b, Akt and mTOR. GLP-1 increases
neurogenesis by activating neurotrophic factors; GDNF, VEGF, and BDNF. GLP-1 also decreases inflammation by decreasing inflammation markers as TNF-a, IL-6, IL-10
and reducing microglial cell activation. GLP-1 also decreases oxidative stress through reducing reactive oxygen species (ROS) and strengthens the integrity of the
blood–brain barrier.
BRAIN INJURY
75
on the outcome. Studies with larger sample sizes conducted at
multiple sites are needed. The effect of GLP-1 may also depend
on the metabolic profile and age of the patients. In one of the
studies that we have currently been recruiting patients with type
2 diabetes diagnosis, we found that patients on GLP-1 agonists
performed worse performance on letter-n-back task and higher
scores on cognitive failures task, compared to patients using
other diabetes medications, but this effect was mediated by the
chronic stress levels of the patients (279). Clinical trials on
human subjects might consider evaluating patients with more
comprehensive biopsychosocial batteries and to study the pro-
tective effects of GLP-1 on patients with prodromal symptoms as
mild cognitive impairment or ultra high-risk psychosis.
As another gap in the literature, many of the preclinical
studies explored the short-term effects of GLP-MA; however,
knowledge about their long-term benefits are limited and
needs to be investigated. A few clinical studies found the
decreased effect or delayed effect of GLP-MA in humans
(Table 9). Because of these inconsistencies, more studies
with longer assessment periods are needed both for preclinical
and clinical studies.
As a last observation, we inspected that generally behavioral
assessments in preclinical studies are limited to the lesion model
and may not cover all aspects of cortical function and all cortical
layers. More studies investigating cortical effects of GLP-1 are
needed at the whole brain level. Since we excluded studies on
mood and reward systems, we may have missed the studies that
searched GLP-1’s effect on other cortical structures, but this may
be counted as a limitation of our strategy.
Finally, even if we could not make a publication bias
statistics due to heterogeneity of the outcome variables of
the studies, we would like to emphasize that; we found only
limited number of studies that reported negative findings of
GLP-1 and neuroprotective effects. Therefore, the presented
work here might be under the effect of publication bias.
Follow-up of clinical trials that have been registered to
a clinical trial database, could be beneficial for seeing the
publication bias in further years. Also, with an aim to include
only articles published in full text as a quality assessment, we
could not give space to poster presentations in this review. We
think that more research will be published in the coming
years, and their findings may affect the general knowledge
on GLP-1 and neuroprotection.
Conclusion
Recent literature shows that GLP-1 and its agonists, DPP-4
inhibitors and combined GLP-1/GIP molecules are effective in
partially or fully reversing the effects of neurotoxic compounds,
neurovascular complications of diabetes, neuropathological
changes related with Alzheimer’s disease or vascular occlusion.
Possible mechanisms that provide neuroprotection are enhan-
cing viability of the neurons and restoring neurite outgrowth by
increased neurotrophic factors, increasing subventricular zone
progenitor cells, decreasing apoptosis, decreasing the level of
pro-inflammatory factors, and strengthening blood-brain bar-
rier. Also, even though the results of clinical studies look pro-
mising, the number of studies on this subject and their sample
size are low, which limits their evidence for clinical practice.
Further clinical trials are needed for a benchside to bedside
translation of recent findings.
